## Bug Report

Please answer these questions before submitting your issue. Thanks!

### 1. Minimal reproduce step (Required)

<!-- a step by step guide for reproducing the bug. -->

This issue is introduced coincidently by https://github.com/pingcap/tidb/pull/64289, so we can only reproduce this issue based on that PR.

After https://github.com/pingcap/tidb/pull/64289, to tolerate time lag between different TiDB, we purposely read some duplicated bindings when loading bindings from storage into memory.

When adding these duplicated bindings into the binding cache, we forget to check whether their digests are already stored in the cache, if yes, we should skip setting them. Since we forget this process, these duplicated bindings in binding cache could accumulate gradually over time, and finally cause long optimization time since the optimizer need more time to match binding.

<img width="1207" height="600" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8c52c091-bb2a-4c12-b9f5-a60ebd364f8d" />

<img width="500" height="268" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b4f95e10-72f9-4f44-8e94-32d46c55423f" />

To reproduce this problem, create some bindings with the same pattern but different database names, and then observe the below log:

```
create database d1;
use d1;
create table t (a int, b int, c int);
create global binding using select * from t;

create database d2;
use d2;
create table t (a int, b int, c int);
create global binding using select * from t;

create database d3;
use d3;
create table t (a int, b int, c int);
create global binding using select * from t;

create database d4;
use d4;
create table t (a int, b int, c int);
create global binding using select * from t;

create database d5;
use d5;
create table t (a int, b int, c int);
create global binding using select * from t;
```

